      "source": [
        "## **Machine Learning Model for Forecasting**\n",
        "\n",
        "A time series forecasting model is trained to predict future climate values (such as temperature anomaly or emissions).\n",
        "The dataset is divided into:\n",
        "1. Training data (past observations)\n",
        "2. Testing data (recent observations)\n",
        "\n",
        "The model learns temporal patterns and generates forecasts for future periods."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 42,
      "id": "b76ce072-2de1-4914-9a0e-6801b12c4c1d",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "b76ce072-2de1-4914-9a0e-6801b12c4c1d",
        "outputId": "59104fd3-54c6-4f55-ea44-7dacad437017",
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 489
        }
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Root Mean Squared Error: 12.11\n"
          ]
        },
        {
          "output_type": "display_data",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "<Figure size 1000x500 with 1 Axes>"
            ],
            "image/png": "\n"
          },
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor\n",
        "from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error\n",
        "\n",
        "# 1. Feature Engineering: Create Lag Features\n",
        "# We use the temperature from 1 month and 12 months ago to help the model learn patterns\n",
        "df_ml = climate_data.copy()\n",
        "df_ml['lag_1'] = df_ml['avg_temp_c'].shift(1)\n",
        "df_ml['lag_12'] = df_ml['avg_temp_c'].shift(12)\n",
        "df_ml = df_ml.dropna()\n",
        "\n",
        "# 2. Define Features and Target\n",
        "X = df_ml[['lag_1', 'lag_12', 'co2_concentration_ppm', 'enso_index']]\n",
        "y = df_ml['avg_temp_c']\n",
        "\n",
        "# 3. Train/Test Split\n",
        "split = int(len(df_ml) * 0.8)\n",
        "X_train, X_test = X[:split], X[split:]\n",
        "y_train, y_test = y[:split], y[split:]\n",
        "\n",
        "# 4. Model Training\n",
        "model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)\n",
        "model.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
        "\n",
        "# 5. Evaluation and Predictions\n",
        "preds = model.predict(X_test)\n",
        "print(f\"Root Mean Squared Error: {np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, preds)):.2f}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "predictions = model.predict(X_test)\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))\n",
        "plt.plot(y_test.index, y_test, label='Actual')\n",
        "plt.plot(y_test.index, predictions, label='Predicted', linestyle='--')\n",
        "plt.title(\"ML Temperature Forecast\")\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "7ab404d3-1747-40df-bc6f-1d8f8692a25b",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "7ab404d3-1747-40df-bc6f-1d8f8692a25b"
      },
      "source": [
        "#### **Explanation**\n",
        "This code implements a machine learning model, specifically a Random Forest Regressor, to forecast the average temperature. Here's a breakdown of what each section does:\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Feature Engineering**: It creates new features by shifting the avg_temp_c column by 1 month (lag_1) and 12 months (lag_12). These 'lag' features help the model learn seasonal and short-term trends from past temperatures. Rows with missing lag values (at the beginning of the DataFrame) are then dropped.\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Define Features (X) and Target (y)**: The input features (X) for the model are lag_1, lag_12, co2_concentration_ppm, and enso_index. The target variable (y) that the model aims to predict is avg_temp_c.\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Train/Test Split**: The dataset is divided into training and testing sets. 80% of the data is used for training the model, and the remaining 20% is reserved for evaluating its performance on unseen data.\n",
